    ],
    comment: '<p>The HTML <code>&#x3C;dfn></code>, or the <strong>Definition</strong> element, is used to specify a term that\'s being defined within the <code>&#x3C;p></code>, <code>&#x3C;section></code> and/or <code>&#x3C;dt></code>/<code>&#x3C;dd></code> pairing elements. Also, the <code>&#x3C;dfn></code> element is usually used to indicate the first use of a term in a document.</p>\n<pre><code class="language-html">&#x3C;p>\n  &#x3C;dfn>Enki&#x3C;/dfn> is an app\n  that provides daily workouts\n  for your dev skills.\n&#x3C;/p>\n</code></pre>\n<p><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="320" height="78"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><rect width="320" height="78" fill="#FFF" rx="9"/><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Italic, Roboto" font-size="16" font-style="italic"><tspan x="20" y="34">Enki</tspan> <tspan x="49.32813" y="34" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto"> is an app that provides daily </tspan> <tspan x="20" y="53" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto">workouts for your dev skills.</tspan></text></g></svg></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The <code>&#x3C;dfn></code> elements main purpose is to provide semantic meaning. Other than that, it has no special functionality.</p>\n<p>Also, the <code>&#x3C;dfn></code> element has a <code>title</code> attribute. If the <code>title</code> attribute is present, the content of the <code>&#x3C;dfn></code> element, which is the value of the <code>title</code> attribute, has to be the term being defined and nothing else.</p>\n<p>Furthermore, the <code>&#x3C;dfn></code> element can have the <code>&#x3C;abbr></code> element nested inside it. If the <code>&#x3C;dfn></code> element has a single <code>&#x3C;abbr></code> element with a <code>title</code> attribute nested inside it, then the value of the <code>&#x3C;abbr></code> elements <code>title</code> attribute is the term being defined.</p>\n<p>Example with abbr:</p>\n<pre><code class="language-html">&#x3C;p>\n  &#x3C;dfn>\n   &#x3C;abbr\n    title="Hypertext Markup Language">\n   HTML\n   &#x3C;/abbr>\n  &#x3C;/dfn>\n  is the standard markup language\n  for creating web pages.\n&#x3C;/p>\n\n&#x3C;p>\n  After a few hours,\n  I was finally able to understand\n  &#x3C;abbr\n   title="Hypertext Markup Language">\n   HTML\n  &#x3C;/abbr>\n  !\n&#x3C;/p>\n</code></pre>\n<p>Abbr Result:</p>\n<p><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="320" height="173"><g fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><rect width="320" height="173" fill="#FFF" rx="9"/><text fill="#000" font-family="Roboto-Italic, Roboto" font-size="16" font-style="italic"><tspan x="20" y="34">HTML</tspan> <tspan x="62.30469" y="34" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto"> is the standard markup </tspan> <tspan x="20" y="53" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto">language for creating web pages.</tspan> <tspan x="20" y="91" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto">... later in the document...</tspan> <tspan x="20" y="129" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto">After a few hours, I was finally able </tspan> <tspan x="20" y="148" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto">to understand </tspan> <tspan x="122.71094" y="148">HTML</tspan> <tspan x="165.01563" y="148" font-family="Roboto-Regular, Roboto"> !</tspan></text><path stroke="#000" stroke-dasharray="1 2" stroke-linecap="square" d="M18.5 36.5h45m58 113.75h45"/></g></svg></p>\n',
